title: For Sale:  Ruger Mini 30 w/ Scope and Wood Stock
postcontent:
Clearing up some room in the safe, getting wife off back, and justifying other recent gun purchases; so I am selling my Ruger Mini-30 in 7.62x39.

I received this gun in a trade with the intention to blast lots of holes in a piece of paper at the price of $.20-.25 a hole, but in the end I have only shot one box of 20 rnds though it just to make sure the gun functions properly (which it did). 

The gun is in great shape with minimal scratching on the bluing, no dents or scratches in the stock, and a nice shiny bore. The wood stock is original and is extremely difficult to find, as I have only located a few complete 30’s with the wood stock of them while having it, so unless you want to drive to Idaho; this is your chance to snatch one up. This gun is in such good shape that I can only surmise that it has spent most of its life acting as a heavy item to keep gun safes from floating away, rather than in the woods or at the range. Reasonably I would say the gun is at 99%. 

The older model Tasco 3-9x40 scope on the other hand is a different story. I can personally guarantee that it has not been sighted in, and looks like it was used as a chew toy for some bionic robot dog somewhere. But it is one of the scopes they made in Japan before they started making junk, so the optics is clear and the up/down, left/right adjustment is clicking and can probably be brought in to center.

The rifle comes with a 5 round Ruger brand flush mount detachable magazine. Asking $850 OBO.

The Smith & Wesson SW99 is a modern, polymer frame pistol that is nearly identical to the Walther P99. The SW99 features an internal striker, as opposed to the classical external hammer. It is chambered in 9mm Para, .40 S&W, and .45 ACP. The pistol lacks a manual safety; instead a de-cocking button is placed on the top rear section of the slide, which when actuated, places the firearm into double-action mode. This mechanism differs with each variation of the action, which will be explained below. The SW99 features several safety features including a loaded chamber indicator on the right side of the slide, a protruding, red-painted cocking indicator, and a drop safety. As with the P99, the cocking indicator does not protrude from the slide of the QA variant unless the weapon is fired, as it is in a constant partially cocked state.[3] The SW99 also features a fully supported chamber design, which leaves no portion of the chambered round exposed. Because of this there is less chance of injury to the shooter and/or destruction of the pistol, should the casing head rupture.

title: For Sale:  1873 Colt Single Action
postcontent: SELLING FROM MY PRIVATE COLLECTION* RARE & IMPORTANT Documented Texas Deputy Sheriff Archibald Adolphus "Archie" Bacon's Colt Single Action Army Revolver, Nickel Plated with Carved Steer Head Pearl Grips and Unique Custom "AAB" Embossed A. Stelzig Houston, Texas Holster/Belt Rig, .41 cal, mfg. 1906 with 5 1/2" barrel. There's nothing better to document ownership of an item than seeing it captured in a vintage photograph, and we have not one but two photos of this rig being worn by it's original owner. Adolphus A. Bacon was born in Missouri on April 4th, 1879, and his family moved to Victoria, Texas just one year later. By 1904, Bacon was serving as a constable in Victoria, soon being elected by Sheriff Bob Weisiger as Deputy Sheriff of Victoria County. Bacon would hold this position until 1912. He then became a rancher for several years, and moved to Houston, Texas in 1925. He took up position as a guard at the National Biscuit Company (now "Nabsico") between 1926 and 1929, and from 1930-1932, Bacon worked as a guard at the Union National Bank in Houston. He passed away February 3rd, 1934. This revolver and holster rig were on his side right from the beginning and saw use through all his Sheriff, ranching, and guard days. It was passed down through the family until being sold in 2012. The gun was originally blued from the factory, but Bacon had it Nickel plated at some point during it's life. Approx. 80%+ of the frosty re-nickel finish remains. Otherwise the gun is completely original with matching serial numbers and clean original screws. The steer head pearl grips are original to the period and fit the gun perfect. They show vibrant color and pleasing wear, and there are five "kill" notches on the left edge. The bottom of the right grip has been chipped in two places and carefully glued back together, and there appears to be traces of blood under the grip. I would assume Bacon hit someone over the head with the butt in a scuffle. The action works well and the cylinder locks up tight, however the last click of the hammer doesn't quite seem to hold. The bore shows strong rifling (slightly worn near the muzzle) with very light scattered black powder frosting. The serial numbers and patent dates are slightly washed from when the gun was refinished, however they are all readable.For only serious buyer .Willing to ship.
